5 Summary of Linear Regression - Part 1¶

Overview:

  • Goal: 1-step ahead consumption prediction in 30 min intervals
  • Scope: everything was done for a single fixed household, call it household X
  • Regressors: temperature, time of the day, day of the year, auto-regressors with different lags
  • Methodology: linear regression

What has been done so far:

  • Data cleaning
  • Feature selection with RFECV and PACF+CV methods
  • Significance analysis
  • Visulaization

Results:

  • The general trend can be modeled
  • Sudden high peaks are underestimated
  • Both feature selection methods obtain similar error measures
  • The number of selected features is less than 20
  • Important features are among 48k +/- 2, k between 0 and 7

To do next: Improving the fit for household X

  • Are outliers the only source of error?
  • 1 hour resolution
  • Modeling the residuals

Robustenss analysis:

  • Effect of weekday
  • Effect of time of the day
  • Comparing error between different households

Federation:

  • Is this problem a good instance for federated learning?

7 Changing The Assumptions¶

In this section, we change some of the general assumptions to evaluate regression robustness or try to improve the fit

7.1 Effect of the part of the day

  • Goal: train separate linear models for different parts of the day
  • Hope: improve the fit (reduce MSE, increase adj. R2)
  • Motivation: (1) different consumption patterns in morning, noon, afternoon, evening, and night (2) the shape of residuals in different parts of the day are not the same
  • Procedure: (1) divide Tuesday data to different parts (2) RFECV feature selection for each part of the day individually (3) train different models on each part
  • Note 1: RFECV searches among temporal features 'hourofd_x', 'hourofd_y', 'dayofy_x','dayofy_y', 'temperature_hourly', and lags 48k +/- 3 for k between 0 and 7
  • Note 2: Dividing to day parts reduces the training set size, so the data from Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday is used in this section
  • Results: morning and evening models have a high MSE, noon is the same as the general model, afternoon is ok and night is perfect.
  • Conclusions: the high error in morning and evening is because a linear model is not sufficient for prediction, not because of the fitting method

7.2 Changing the selected weekday

  • So far everything was done for Thursdays
  • Questions: (1) Is prediction on all days equally challenging? (2) Is the consumption pattern different among days?
  • How to answer? (1) repeat lin reg on all days, test on the same day (2) what will happen if we train on one day and test on another?
  • Procedure: (1) divide data to different days, (2) train linear model + RFECV using data from each day, (3) test model on all days
  • Results (diagonal): Mon, Tue, Sat are easier to predict; Thurs (that we worked with) is the hardest
  • Results (off-diagonal): Fri and Wed are different from other days, might be because of different school schedule

Discussions¶

1. Are nonlinear models needed?

  • Intuition: yes; linear models cannot capture the peaks at some parts of the day so nonlinear models might be needed. Lin reg + FL is not good, maybe nonlin+FL works well.
  • How to test: use GP on residuals or GP with a kernel that has a linear part

2. Is this dataset useful for FL?

  • Observation: applying the model trained to predict mean consumption of 10 houses for predicting the consumption of household X results in a high MSE
  • Conclusion: hoping to learn lin. reg. coefficients with FL is too much
  • How to test: fix a set of features, train individual models for different houses using this set of features, check if the distribution of hyperparams is narrow

3. Motivation for FL: training a GP needs two years of data. Does having the optimal hyperparameters reduce the number of needed samples?

4. Modeling the residuals:

  • Either residual of predicting with the individually-trained or FL linear model
  • Are the residuals different from white noise? if not, no hope to predict them
  • Use days/part of days when residuals are more different from WGN
